Title: The TESS Keck Survey I: Masses, Densities, and Orbits of Three Sub-Neptune Sized Transiting Planets in TOI-561
Authors: Lauren M. Weiss, Fei Dai, the TESS Keck Survey, and others

Abstract: Systems with multiple transiting planets provide excellent natural laboratories for testing the physics of planet formation, since the planets all formed around the same star and from the same protoplanetary disk.  Furthermore, the formation of ultra-short period planets (USPs), which are primarily rocky planets with orbital periods $<1 $ day, is poorly understood.  The NASA \TESS\ Mission has discovered TOI-561, a multi-planet system containing a USP.  This bright ($V=10.2$) star hosts three small transiting planet candidates: TOI-561 b (P=0.4 days, \rpl=1.6\,\rearth), c (P=10.8 days, \rpl= 3.2\,\rearth), and d (P=16.4 days, \rpl=2.8\,\rearth).  With radial velocities obtained on Keck/HIRES and [other facilities welcome], we confirm the planetary nature of all three candidates.  Planet b has \mpl= and \rhopl = , which are consistent with a rocky composition.  Planet c has \mpl= and \rhopl=, and planet d has \mpl= and \rhopl=), both of which are consistent with an interior rocky core overlaid with a low-mass volatile envelope.  The masses, radii, and orbits of the TOI-561 planets can be used to constrain the history of the system, and in particular to elucidate how the USP arrived at its present orbit.

Hi Lauren,

My preliminary modeling shows that our best estimates for Teff and L (from Gaia) are hard to reconcile with the measured [Fe/H] from Specmatch. I then noticed that TOI-561 has high Gaia proper motion:

PM_RA: -108.432 0.088
PM_DE: -61.511 0.094

Combining this with the Gaia RV makes the star kinematically consistent with the thick disc (see https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.07825). To confirm this, it'd be great to measure alpha-element abundances from the HIRES spectra. I can look into this, but it'd probably quicker and more reliable to ask John Brewer to run SME. If the star is indeed alpha-enhanced this would remove the discrepancy since it would enhance the bulk metallicity [M/H] (used by the interior models); it would be also be a nice spin on this system since there aren't many known multis around old, thick disc stars.

Hi Lauren,

My preliminary modeling shows that our best estimates for Teff and L (from Gaia) are hard to reconcile with the measured [Fe/H] from Specmatch. I then noticed that TOI-561 has high Gaia proper motion:

PM_RA: -108.432 0.088
PM_DE: -61.511 0.094

Combining this with the Gaia RV makes the star kinematically consistent with the thick disc (see https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.07825). To confirm this, it'd be great to measure alpha-element abundances from the HIRES spectra. I can look into this, but it'd probably quicker and more reliable to ask John Brewer to run SME. If the star is indeed alpha-enhanced this would remove the discrepancy since it would enhance the bulk metallicity [M/H] (used by the interior models); it would be also be a nice spin on this system since there aren't many known multis around old, thick disc stars.

Title: The TESS Keck Survey I: Masses, Densities, and Orbits of Three Sub-Neptune Sized Transiting Planets in TOI-561
Authors: Lauren M. Weiss, Fei Dai, the TESS Keck Survey, and others

Abstract: Systems with multiple transiting planets provide excellent natural laboratories for testing the physics of planet formation, since the planets all formed around the same star and from the same protoplanetary disk.  Furthermore, the formation of ultra-short period planets (USPs), which are primarily rocky planets with orbital periods $<1 $ day, is poorly understood.  The NASA \TESS\ Mission has discovered TOI-561, a multi-planet system containing a USP.  This bright ($V=10.2$) star hosts three small transiting planet candidates: TOI-561 b (P=0.4 days, \rpl=1.6\,\rearth), c (P=10.8 days, \rpl= 3.2\,\rearth), and d (P=16.4 days, \rpl=2.8\,\rearth).  With radial velocities obtained on Keck/HIRES and [other facilities welcome], we confirm the planetary nature of all three candidates.  Planet b has \mpl= and \rhopl = , which are consistent with a rocky composition.  Planet c has \mpl= and \rhopl=, and planet d has \mpl= and \rhopl=), both of which are consistent with an interior rocky core overlaid with a low-mass volatile envelope.  The masses, radii, and orbits of the TOI-561 planets can be used to constrain the history of the system, and in particular to elucidate how the USP arrived at its present orbit.

The overleaf link for the paper is here: https://www.overleaf.com/project/5e03de1c6dd7730001d997b3, Submitted to the TFOP Publications Page:

I tried to run this through Grand to get some better APF velocities, but they came out much worse than with the regular doppler code. I've attached a plot for reference (iteration 10 is what you should look at). I suspect that this is because the S/N is much lower for these observations compared to 25463. This might improve with a lot more (~100) observations, but I'm not sure that's worth it.

The next thing to try would be to change our primary doppler code to use larger chunk widths. Hope you're doing well. We noticed that there are 33 APF observations of TOI 1135 reported on the SG2/SG4 sheet. Are these your data (or your collaborators)?

You've probably noticed that it's a relatively young star. Based on Li EW and rotation, it appears to be roughly around Praesepe/Hyades age. We're interested in the system as well, but given that you're pretty far along toward a mass measurement (hope that's panning out!), we were considering Doppler tomography observations to measure the obliquity rather than going after an orbit. If you have already scheduled or obtained spectroscopy during transit yourself, that could influence our plans to do the same. In the interest of not wasting/duplicating effort, would you be willing to share your plans for this system?

Lets get a real HIRES template.  It will take 8-10 min., Needs Vetting Spectra, We currently observe 54 m/s of scatter for this target.  Based on the my eyeball estimate from the attached plot from Hillenbrand et al. (2015) using logR'HK = -4.57, we should expect 7-18 m/s of scatter.   The logR'HK will vary somewhat over the rotational and magnetic cycles of the star, but the activity would have to be much stronger (logR'HK = -4.2) to explain all of the observed scatter.  I think we may be seeing some significant Doppler signals from planets (and TESS photometry suggests three transiting planets).  If we are to contend with the Prot = 7 day signal, we will need high-cadence observations.  I suggest resuming APF observations.  Even if the APF has a hard time getting high-precision RVs, it will be useful to constrain the activity model used in the HIRES+APF model.

comment_list:
Paraphrasing a note from Sam Quinn: 
TOI-1169 is attributed to a fake star i.e. the blended combination (TIC 302518439, Tmag=10.4) of two real stars (TIC 802647157, Tmag=10.6 and TIC 802647158, Tmag=11.3). From Sam's calculations, this means the actual transit depth is more like ~1.3% if it's on TIC 802647157 and ~2.3% if on TIC 802647158 (compared to ~1% on the fake, blended star). See the screenshot below for the TIC8 entries. TIC 302518439, the fake star, is the result of imperfect automated matching between different source catalogs: unresolved stars of near equal brightness may be listed in e.g. 2MASS as a single source, but are resolved by DR2 as two sources, meaning the automated cross-matching produces three "stars" in the end. All this being said, the event is still v-shaped and Sam has turned off TOI-1169 on the SG2/4 spreadsheets, but we should keep this scenario in mind when evaluating the DV reports for TOIs with close companions., Observed for Peter Plavchan.  Likely unresolved binary and false positive.

comment_list:
An email from Karen Collins (SG1 lead) to Andrew Howard from Nov. 24, 2019 is pasted below.  The tl;dr version is that this target is likely a false positive.
---------------------------------------
TTF Note: [Andrew Howard interested in preliminary check before DT run.] Detect the event on target with extreme precision (<0.5ppt/5min) or clear the field of NEBs, especially the neighbors 9" N and 16" NW. In other words, you will likely need to observe focused to clear the field. Full transits are preferred, but partials with more than 50% in-transit may also be useful.
Justin Wittrock observed a full on 20191103 in R and detected a possible ~250 ppt NEB in the T3/T4 neighboring pair 16" NW of target. This is about the right depth to cause the TESS detection. Note that the apparent early egress in the target star light curve was likely caused by a shift in pointing at that time, and is unlikely to be astrophysical.
Investigating the TESS FFIs using an r=0.5 pixel aperture appears to rule out the 770 ppm event on target and suggests a ~2000 ppm undeblended depth in the T3/T4 neighboring pair 16" NW of target (see in-line finder field and light curve below).
Andrew H., this candidate is looking like it will get confirmed as an NEB. We normally use the disposition possible NEB (PNEB) after the first detection of an apparent NEB, and then move to NEB after a second detection confirms it wasn't just a chance alignment with the TESS ephemeris. If we can show from further analysis of the TESS data that the NEB is off target, sometimes we will move the disposition directly to NEB after a single observation. I think the T3 light curve from FFIs shown below suggests that the event is in the neighboring star, but out of an abundance of caution, I'll leave it active to try to get a confirmation of the NEB at a second epoch, unless you feel these data are enough to convince you to abandon your DT run.
PC => PNEB
The next observation should be a full transit in a red (r', R, i', I, z) filter to confirm the return of the PNEB on the neighbor 16" NW.
Karen, This object is a potentially interesting obliquity target with Vsini = 12 and a predicted RM amplitude of 8 m/s.  The star is V = 9.7 and the planet is approximately Neptune size with P = 2 days.  It looks like its in the sub-Neptune desert or at least a region of low occurrence with an insolation flux of ~2000 time the Earth value.  Theres a transit opportunity during Christmas night 2019 when were on the telescope., An email from Karen Collins:
--------------------------------------
Khalid Barkaoui and the TRAPPIST-North team observed a full on 20191124 and reconfirmed the ~on-time arrival of the NEB 16" NW of the target. This combined the consistent generally direction of the QLP offsets and the FFI analysis give a strong conclusion of NEB.
PNEB => NEB (and retired)

The star shows clear photometric variability of around 10 days, so I'm guessing this 9.27d signal is stellar activity even at K-band.

- Peter

What SNR per spectrum is desired for this target?  If the companion has dV = 5,  SNR_contamination = 100.  The target could be observed with counts=60k (SNR_Poisson = 100), and the total SNR would be ~100/sqrt(2)., Here's a an assessment of two potential issues with this target. (1) is the target dV < 5? and (2) can we be sure the transit is occurring around the brighter component. 

# 1. What's the contrast? 

a) the primary star is ~K1 with M_V = 5.9, M_I = 5.0, M_K = 4.0, R ~ 0.85 Rsun.
b) assuming the companion is bound and main-sequence at delta-K of 3.7, the secondary is an M4V with M_V = 12.8, M_I = 10.0, M_K 7.7, R ~ 0.24 Rsun
c) so delta V ~ 6.9

# 2. Is the transit around the primary? 

a) Depth diluted depth is is d = 800e-6
b) Assuming transit is around the primary, Rp = sqrt(d) * R_star = 2.6 Re a garden-variety sub-Neptune
c) Assuming transit is around the secondary, the true depth larger by a factor of 100x because delta-I ~ 5mag. So Rp = sqrt(100 * d) * R_star = 7.3 Re. 
d) While we cannot rule out that it's a planet around the secondary directly, 7.3 Re objects are very rare around M4V stars. Also, a model comparison of the light curve fits with different levels of dilution could be more definitive.

If someone on our team is interested in leading a paper, please speak up.  Given that that Hara's team had 290 SOPHIE RVs in their paper, and are planning to get more, it seems unlikely that our RVs are going to add substantially more information to the system.  On the other hand, maybe Ashley would like to do an asteroseismic analysis in a contribution to the second SOPHIE team paper or as a standalone paper. 
If there's interest, let's pursue a paper.  If not, let's contribute our RVs to the SOPHIE team., Recent TOI release has revealed a new transiting inner planet. One of the special aspects of this system is the chain of 3:2 mean motion resonances. The orbital period of the new (1.3 Earth radius) inner planet is 2.18 days, which further adds to the chain since it's in 3:2 resonance with the inner 3.4 day period RV planet. So the chain is even longer than expected! This is part of our APT program monitoring TESS known exoplanet hosts and so I have request with Dave Latham that we lead the discovery paper, for which we can also include the HIRES data. I sent Dave the request on Dec 5th and still awaiting response., Andrew Howard emailed Hara for the SOPHIE data, and I put it onto Cadence and spooled up a RadVel file. Results now available., https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.13296
New paper by Hara et. al "The SOPHIE search for northern extrasolar planets. XVII. A compact planetary system in a near 3:2 mean motion resonance chain" 
They are claiming 4 planets and a possible fifth., Though I looked, I could not find that the Hara paper includes the SOPHIE velocities used in their analysis of this system., Hara paper indicates candidate RV signals at 18 and 35 days. This could be planets, or the rotation period., Web TESS viewing tool suggests 6 total sectors of data, doubling the asteroseismic detection probability (>0.5). This is now a high priority target for Ashley's Thesis, This is an ATL (asteroseismic target list) target with a fairly decent detection probability and because it has already known planets, would make the asteroseismic detection more valuable. I've had a look at the single sector and see some power excess where we expect (~2000 muHz), but it's too soon to tell. If there is any interest within the group on this system, let's chat. I think we expect a few more sectors for this target so we may be able to get some asteroseismic constraints!, I received the message below from Nathan Hara:
---------------
Dear Andrew, 

Things are pretty good in Switzerland, thanks for your concern. I hope youre doing well too. 

You are right about the data, there seems to have been a misunderstanding between A&A and us, so that the the data is not online yet.I have attached the data points analysed in our paper. 

Also, Ill let you know that the SOPHIE consortium is also planning to do a follow-up analysis with more TESS data. We have been contacted by Jennifer Burt, Chelsea Huang (MIT) and Sam Quinn from CfA, who are interested in participating to the analysis. SOPHIE observations have resumed a couple of weeks ago, so that we should have a few dozen more points by the end of July. Were also in discussion with the HARPS-N team to add about 30 measurements. Maybe we could coordinate our papers, to avoid unnecessary duplications. Let me know what you think!

Best,
Nathan

Abstract of Heidari et al. (in prep.) posted to the MIT Spacebook:

We present the discovery and characterization of a transiting sub-Neptune-sized planet around TOI-1611 (also known as HD207897 or TIC 264678534), based on photometry and radial velocity measurements obtained by the short cadence of Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite (TESS) and SOPHIE high precision spectrograph. The host star is a bright (V=8.37) K0 dwarf which was continuously observed by TESS during sectors 18 and 19 while it was initially monitored in the context of the SOPHIE exoplanet consortiums dedicate to explore of low-mass planets which obtained 44 high-resolution spectra over 3 years. By using the transit least squares (TLS) algorithm and considering the stellar host characteristics, we find that TOI-1611b is a mini- Neptune planet with radii of 2.2 R_Earth and orbits around its host star at a period of 16.2 days. We analyze the RV SOPHIE measurements, establish the planetary nature of this TESS candidate, and measure a planetary mass of 19.7 M_Earth. A simultaneous joint model of photometry and RVs data using two different packages, PASTIS and EXOFAST V2 in order to increase the precision of the planetary parameter is done., Summarizing some Slack discussion:
Howard notes: "CFOP working group SG2/4 just posted a note about TOI-1611 (CPS name= 207897). A Masters student from IAC in Spain, lead by Enric Palle will be writing it up using archival SOPHIE data. I think we should consider offering our HIRES data to their paper. We have seven HIRES RVs taken in 2004-2015. This may not be helpful for mass determination, but it may help constrain long term companions.  This target to  far North(dec=~84), making it challenging to observe at Keck."
Andrew noted that it looks like a great target if the planet is real.  We should collect a few more RVs and contribute to Palle et al.  If the planet pans out, let's include it in TKS.
Teo noted that it was rejected from TKS because of 5-sigma odd-even variation in QLP, but will be reconsidered in SPOC.

comment_list:
The discussion from Howard & Fulton (2016) [https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016PASP..128k4401H/abstract] states:
55 Cancri hosts five known planets (Fischer et al. 2009) with at least one that transits (Winn et al. 2011). The orbital periods are P = 0.74,14.6, 44, 260, and 5200 days. The middle three planets (b, c, and f) are approximately Saturn-mass while the innermost, transiting planet (e) is a super-Earth and the outermost planet (d) is a super-Jupiter., The orbital period of the inner super-Earth was initially misreported.  Dawson & Fabrycky (2010) identified it as an ultra-short period planet and (correctly) attributed the error to a daily alias.  https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2010ApJ...722..937D/abstract, Here's a really nice review of the 55 Cnc system (also named Copernicus?!), including the many misinterpretations of this system before our present understanding, by Debra Fischer: https://arxiv.org/pdf/1807.11925.pdf, This is part of Lauren's RV-multis-bright program.
There is an emerging planet candidate at 7700 days, K = 20 m/s.  This is not activity as initially reported in Baluev (2015), because the S-values clearly have a period of only 10 years.  Also, activity signals do not have amplitudes of 20 m/s.  This is also not the companion star (55 Cnc B), which is 85" away, which, at a parallax of 80 mas aka 12.5 pc, has separation 85" = 1000 AU, which has P >>> 20 years.  At 20 m/s and P=20 years, this has msini of ~a couple Jupiters., Winn et al. (2012) identified transits of the inner planet e - https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2011ApJ...737L..18W/abstract

Knutson et al. (2014) measured the atmospheric transmission spectrum of this super-Earth in the 1.1-1.7um range using the WFC3 instrument on HST over two visits.  The spectrum appeared flat (perhaps due to clouds) and was inconsistent at the 10-sigma level with a solar-composition atmosphere (mostly H/He) having the expected scale height. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2014ApJ...794..155K/abstract, Super-Earth with Msin i = 8.2  1.2 M and P = 9.494  0.005 days discovered by Howard et al. (2011) using Keck-HIRES RVs. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2011ApJ...730...10H/abstract, Henry et al. (2011) found transits of HD 97658 b using ground-based photometry from the Automated Photometric Telescope (APT)!!  Five partial transits were observed and all showed egress at 2-3.5 sigma significance.  Four other epoch were observed under similar conditions, when transits were not predicted, and transits were not detected!   Combining the five nights with predicted transits gave a 5.5-sigma detection with a transit depth of 1470  260 ppm.  The four nights without transits were consistent with flat and gave a transit depth of 400  398 ppm. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2011arXiv1109.2549H/abstract
However, this discovery was later shown to be wrong by follow-up observations by MOST and Spitzer. 
Note that the submission to ApJ of Henry et al. (2012) was withdrawn and the paper now only lives on arXiv., Stellar activity FP, After the non-detection of transits of HD 97658b by MOST and Spitzer, the search continued.  Remarkably, both space telescopes discovered transits, but at a slightly different ephemeris (that is inconsistent with the transits from Henry et al. (2011)).  
Dragomir et al. (2013) found transits with MOST. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2013ApJ...772L...2D/abstract
Van Grootel et al. (2014) using Spitzer observations to confirm transits consistent with the MOST detection. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2014ApJ...786....2V/abstract
